definition.value: A lymph node that is located deeper within the organism, further from the surface.
A parotid lymph node that is located superficially.
A lymph node that is medial to the gluteus superficialis m., caudal to gluteus medius m. and sciatic nerve lymph node.
One of the lymph nodes that form a chain around the ileocolic artery.

The paraaortic lymph nodes (also known as para-aortic, periaortic, and peri-aortic) are a group of lymph nodes that lie in front of the lumbar vertebral bodies near the aorta. These lymph nodes receive drainage from the lower gastrointestinal tract and the pelvic organs.

The mastoid lymph nodes (retroauricular lymph nodes, posterior auricular glands), usually two in number, are situated on the mastoid insertion of the Sternocleidomastoideus, beneath the Auricularis posterior. Their afferent vessels drain the posterior part of the temporoparietal region, the upper part of the cranial surface of the auricula or pinna, and the back of the external acoustic meatus; their efferents pass to the superior deep cervical glands.

The deep parotid lymph nodes are lymph nodes found below the parotid gland. The afferents of the subparotid glands drain the nasal part of the pharynx and the posterior parts of the nasal cavities. Their efferents pass to the superior deep cervical glands.

The preauricular deep parotid lymph nodes (anterior auricular glands or preauricular glands), from one to three in number, lie immediately in front of the tragus. Their afferents drain the lateral surface of the auricula and the skin of the adjacent part of the temporal region; their efferents pass to the superior deep cervical glands.
The infra-auricular deep parotid lymph nodes are a group of lymph nodes found underneath the ear.

The submental lymph nodes (or suprahyoid) are situated between the anterior bellies of the Digastrici. Their afferents drain the central portions of the lower lip and floor of the mouth and the apex of the tongue. Their efferents pass partly to the submandibular lymph nodes and partly to a gland of the deep cervical group situated on the internal jugular vein at the level of the cricoid cartilage.

A lymph node that is part of a forelimb.

A life cycle stage that starts at completion of development and growth of the sexually mature adult animal, and ends before senescence.
A membranous sac in animals that serves as the receptacle of a liquid or contains gas.
A portion of organism substance that is secreted by a reproductive gland.
A part of an organism or organ that is continuous with its surroundings and distinguished from its surroundings based on morphology.
Any substance in the body or expelled from the body that is in a gaseous state.
The stage of being no more dependent of the nest and/or from caregivers for subsistence while having not reach sexual maturity.
Nursing stage that follows the neonate stage in mammals and ends at weaning.
An multicellular anatomical structure that has subparts of multiple organs as a part.
A collection of anatomical structures that are alike in terms of their morphology or developmental origin.
A region or zone on the surface of an organism that encompasses skin and any adnexa, down through muscles and bounded by underlying skeletal support structures.
Any gaseous product of an excretory process.
Any excreted gas that is produced by the digestive tract.
In mammals, mostly produced as a byproduct of bacterial fermentation in the gastrointestinal (GI) tract, especially the colon, and excreted through the rectum
The intraglandular deep parotid lymph nodes are a group of lymph nodes found inside the parotid gland.
A lymph node located in the area below the clavicle.
A lymph node located in the back of the head adjacent to the trapezius muscle.
Any of the lymph nodes of the breast located under the ribcage, near the sternum.

A lymph node located in the superior mediastinum that collects lymph from the thymus, the pericardium, and the right side of the heart.
